This approach doesn't handle scenarios where a container is declared, but no member functions involving hashing are explicitly called. For example, [this](https://godbolt.org/z/Kb366e5rY) compiles.

I suggest a more defensive approach relying on the [conditions](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/utility/hash.html) that must be satisfied for the `std::hash<CTransactionRef>` specialization to be enabled:
```c++
template <>
struct hash<CTransactionRef> {
    hash() = delete;
};
```

Here are two examples on https://godbolt.org/:
- A container with the default hasher: [fails](https://godbolt.org/z/b3Yr3anPv).
- A container with the custom hasher: [passes](https://godbolt.org/z/WYxfbj9P4).
